<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="479" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d479">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State of the South African
                                    Republic</gloss>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-29"><hi rend="italic">January 29,
                                1896</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Highly appreciate your courteous cablegram of to-day. Contents are noted.
                            Take this opportunity to commend to your gracious consideration arrested
                            Americans, who, if they have inadvertently given your Government any
                            cause for complaint, must certainly be acquitted of all complicity in
                            any political designs against a Republic for which the United States can
                            bear only the friendliest feelings.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Olney.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>